    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indeed, the binding process is a crucial part of the mechanism. Ibuprofen acts as a competitive inhibitor, meaning it competes with arachidonic acid for the active site of the COX enzyme. When ibuprofen binds to the COX active site, it prevents arachidonic acid from entering and being converted into prostaglandins. The ibuprofen molecule fits into the active site due to its structural similarity to arachidonic acid, thanks to its carboxyl group that mimics the acid's carboxyl group and the rest of the molecule fitting into the hydrophobic pocket of the enzyme. This prevents the usual enzymatic reaction from occurring, thereby reducing the production of prostaglandins and, as a result, lessening pain and inflammation.",
      "source": "target",
